Name: Mexico SE Indice de Precios y Cotizaciones (IPC)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1930 To Dec 1984
Daily From Jan 1985 To Oct 2020
Metadata: Sources include Annuario Estadistico de los Estados Unidos Mexicanos, Mexico: Direccion General de Estadistica (1930-1939), Revista de Estadistica Mexico: Direccion General de Estadistica (1940-1971), Banco de Mexico, Indicadores Economicos, Mexico: Banco de Mexico (1972-1992). The general index used before 1972 was a weighted aggregative index with a moving base, chain-linked to the original base, weighted by the value of shares of all companies included and adjusted for new capital and share dividends.  The index was based upon daily prices in Mexico City and compiled by Nacional Financiera. The monthly index was an average of weekly figures.  The current IPC (Indice de Precios y Cotizaciones) Index, which covers about 40 issues, begins in 1972. The base is October 31, 1978 = .78162. Monthly data, including high/low/close are provided from 1972 through 1984. This is a capitalization-weighted price index that includes the 40 representative stocks based upon trading value and volume as well as capitalization, using the Paasche formula with chaining.  Adjustments are made for capitalization changes, and components are reviewed every two months.  The "Indice de Precios y Cotizaciones" (IPC) (price and quotes index) is calculated from a sample of shares of enterprises designed for this purpose. The sample used to calculate the IPC is made up of securities representing various sectors of the economy, and is revised twice a year. If a security no longer conforms to the selection criteria, it is replaced by one that does. The relative weight of each stock series in the IPC sample is determined by its market capitalization. The index has national coverage. The base year for the IPC is October 1978 = 0.78. The Mexican Stock Exchange (BMV), located in Mexico City, is responsible for preparing the IPC.  The IPC is considered the broadest indicator of the overall performance of the Mexican Stock Exchange, as reflected in the change in price of a balanced weighted selection (or sampling) of shares that are representative of all the shares listed on the Mexican Stock Exchange.

Name: Australia ASX All-Ordinaries (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1825 To Dec 1831
Daily From Dec 1831 To Jan 1832
Monthly From Feb 1832 To Jan 1958
Daily From Jan 1958 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
Source: D. McL. Lamberton. Share Price Indices in Australia (Sydney: Law Book Co. of Australasia Pty. Ltd., 1958) and â€œ Economic Growth and Stock Prices: The Australian Experienceâ€, Jour. Bus. Univ. Chicago, xxxi, 3 ( July, 1958).
The All Ordinaries index is Australia's premier market indicator. The index represents the 500 largest companies listed on the Australian Stock Exchange. Market capitalisation is the only eligibility requirement of constituents, as liquidity is not considered, with the exception of foreign domiciled companies. The index comprised 99% of the Australian market at June 30, 2002. The old Sydney indices were replaced in 1958 with a new set of indices that were calculated back to July 1936 by Lamberton and covered over 20 sectors. Data were calculated back to 1875 on a monthly basis for the industrial and commercial index, and daily data began in January 1958. The historical data and a description of the indices, as well as other Australian indices, can be found in D. McL. Lamberton, Share Price Indices in Australia, Sydney: Law Book Co., 1958. Monthly data have been taken from the Sydney Stock Exchange Journal, Australian Stock Exchange Journal, Personal Investing, and SXJ Journal, which are the various journals published by the Sydney and Australian stock exchanges. The All-Ordinaries Price Index was capitalization-weighted using the Paasche formula with chaining, which is adjusted for capitalization changes. The index includes the top stocks by capitalization, covering about 92% of domestic companies by market value. Shares should have an aggregate market value of at least 0.02% of all domestic equities on the Exchange, and maintain an average turnover in excess of 0.5% of it quoted shares each month. Components are reviewed monthly. In 1995, the index included 70 Mining stocks, 15 Resource stocks and 233 Industrials. In 1980, indices for all shares traded in Australia were introduced to replace the sector indices for Sydney, Melbourne, and Brisbane. Between 1958 and 1979, resource and energy stocks increased their share of the Australian stock exchanges capitalization, and since these shares were not represented by the old Sydney indices, and they were no longer representative of the stock market's behavior. For this reason, the All-Australia indices were introduced, and these are the indices currently being used. The new price indices were based at December 31, 1979 = 500 and the accumulation indices are based at December 31, 1979 = 1000; however, where possible we have tied the old Sydney stock exchange indices to the current indices to produce a long-term index. The Small Cap and Large Cap indices have a base of December 31, 1990 = 1000 and the Value and Growth indices have a base of December 31, 1995 = 1000. Volume data are available for All-Ordinaries, All Industry, and All-Resources from April 1976 on. The Oil and Gas Index uses the old Brisbane Oil Index because there was no oil index for the Sydney exchange. The Statex Price Index has been appended to the 50 Leaders index, and the Statex Accumulation Index has been appended to the All-Ordinaries Accumulation Index. Size indices were introduced in April 1995 which now include the 20 largest companies (20 Leaders), 50 Largest Companies (50 Leaders-over $1 billion market capitalization), second 50 largest companies (Midcap 50, between $400 million and $1 billion), 100 largest companies (ASX-100) and all other companies (Small Cap, less than $400 million). For more information on the indices, see Australian Associated Stock Exchanges, The Australian Stock Exchange Indices, Sydney: AASE, 1980 and Australian Stock Exchange Limited, ASX Indices & Yields, Sydney: ASX, 1995. Monthly data have been taken from the Sydney Stock Exchange Journal, Australian Stock Exchange Journal, Personal Investing, and SXJ Journal, which are the various journals published by the Sydney and Australian stock exchanges. The data are also available in the ASX Price and Indices Yearbook, which is published annually by the Australian Stock Exchange.
Data from the GFD Indices for Australia, using Australian stocks that were listed in London, is used from 1825 until 1936. This data for mining and finance stocks is combined with data from Lamberton for Commercial/Industrial stocks from 1875 to 1936 to get an index of Australian stocks. The dividend yield from the GFD Indices is used to calculate the total return from 1825 to 1936.

Name: OMX Helsinki All-Share Price Index
Periodicity:
Monthly From Oct 1912 To Dec 1986
Daily From Jan 1987 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The Helsinki Stock Exchange General Index is a capitalization-weighted index consisting of all the stocks traded on the exchange. It is a broad-based index which is broken down into sixteen industry groups. The index was developed with a base level of 1,000 as of December 28, 1990.
Data from 1912 to March 1970 uses calculations from Peter Nyberg and Mika Vaihekoski: "A new value-weighted total return index for the Finnish stock market". Research in International Business and Finance, 2010, vol. 24, no. 3, 267-283. doi: 10.1016/j.ribaf.2009.12.006. The Value-weighted price index is used.
The HEX index is a capitalization-weighted price index of all shares listed on the Helsinki Stock Exchange using the Paasche formula with daily chaining. Adjustments are made for capitalization and component changes. For information on the HEX indices, see Hannu Hernesniemi, "HEX: the Helsinki Stock Exchange's New Index," Finland National Bank Monthly Review (March 1991): 7-11. Data were calculated back to 1987 when the new index was initiated. The index consisted of 18 bank, industrial and other shares from 1921 to 1932 as published in Finland's Monthly Bulletin. From 1933 until 1986 the index uses the Unitas index. This index was a weighted average of price relatives, adjusted for share dividends and rights based upon Friday buying quotations in Helsinki. The index was compiled by the Pohjoismaiden Yhdyspankki and was based on 9 industrial shares and one bank share through. The indices were revised in the spring of 1960 to include 3 bank and 15 industrial shares, in 1971 to include 3 bank, 17 industrial and 5 commercial shares (Unitas, Vol. 43, No. 4, 1971, pp. 206-208), and in 1977 to ten sectors, including all shares traded on the Helsinki Stock Exchange (61 at the time) (Unitas, Vol. 49, No. 3, pp. 135-138). The Unitas index is used through December 1986, and the HEX General index is used starting in January 1987. No data are available from December 1939 until March 1940 due to the war. Volume data are for stocks and bonds from 1931 to September 1966, for stocks only through October 1987, and for stocks and bonds from 1987 on, showing how many 1000 FIM of shares were traded each month. Sources include Statistisches Reichsamt (1921-1932), Unitas (1933-1990), Suomen Pankki (Monthly Bulletin) Helsinki: Suomen Pankki.
Data for the HEX indices are taken from Finland National Bank's Monthly Review. Data before 1987 use the UNITAS sector data. The Helsinki Stock Exchange also calculates the HEX-20, which includes the 20 shares with the highest turnover with share components being selected in January and July. The HEX indices were reorganized and new indices were introduced in January 1997 with data calculated back to June 17, 1996. The old Insurance and Investment index was separated into Insurance and Investment indices. The Other Services index was separated into Transport, Trade and Other Services. Other Industries was broken down into Energy, Food Industry, Construction, Telecommunications and Electronics, Chemicals, Media and Publishing, and Other Industries. The Helsinki Stock Exchange (HEX) indices have a base date of December 28, 1990 = 1000

Name: Netherlands All-Share Price Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1890 To Dec 1913
Monthly From Jan 1914 To Dec 1979
Daily From Jan 1980 To Oct 2020
Metadata: No data are available for the All-Share index from May until August 1940 and from August 1944 to April 1946 when the stock exchange was closed.  The pre-war index was a weighted arithmetic index calculated by the Central Bureau of Statistics and consisted of 50 stocks with a base of 1921-25 = 100, which was a general index of all sectors traded in the Netherlands.  The post-war index was an all-share index as calculated by the Central Bureau of Statistics based upon 27 industrial stocks as well as non-industrial, and was an arithmetic average of daily index prices.  The ANP-CBS All-Share index is used currently. The current all-share index covers 137 shares and has data back-calculated to 1952. Sources include International Statistical Institute (1919-1924), Central Bureau of Statistics, Maandschrift, Amsterdam: CBS (1924-). Data from 1914 to 1918 were calculated by GFD based upon stocks listed on the London Stock Exchange

Name: Madrid SE IBEX-35
Periodicity: Daily From Jan 1987 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The IBEX-35 is a capitalization-weighted price index of the 35 most traded stocks on the continuous electronic trading system of the 4 Spanish exchanges. It uses the Paasche formula with changing and makes adjustments for capitalization changes, but no price changes for convertible bonds; components are reviewed every six months. Three sector indices are now calculated as well. The base is December 31, 1989 = 3000.

Name: Swiss Market Index
Periodicity: Daily From Jan 1988 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The Swiss Market Index is a capitalization-weighted index of the largest and most liquid stocks traded on the Electronic Bourse System. The equities use free float shares in the index calculation. The SMI was developed with a base value of 1,500 as of June 30, 1988.

Name: NASDAQ Composite Index (w/NQB extension)
Periodicity:
Weekly From Oct 1938 To Oct 1948
Monthly From Oct 1948 To Mar 1949
Daily From Mar 1949 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
NASDAQ initiated its sector indices on February 5, 1971 and all the indices use that date as their base except for the Telecommunications index (formerly the Utilities Index) which was rebased to October 29, 1993 = 200 (the Telecommunications index can be converted into the old Utilities index by multiplying the data by 5.74805). The indices are capitalization weighted and include all shares traded on the NASDAQ; however, because the indices are capitalization weighted, they act more like large-cap tech indices than small-cap indices since Intel, Microsoft and other shares represent a substantial portion of the NASDAQ index. All the primary NASDAQ indices are provided complete from their beginning.
Prior to the introduction of the NASDAQ indices, the National Quotation Board, which oversees the over-the-counter market, kept two indices of OTC stocks, one of 35 industrials and one of 15 insurance stocks. The industrial stock average was introduced on November 7, 1948 using the Dow method of price weighting and a divisor using the OTC stocks with the largest market value, largest number of stockholders and the most substantial quotation records. The index was calculated backwards to October 1, 1938 making calculations on the first, tenth and twentieth of each month. For more information on the NQB/OTC industrials index, see National Quotation Bureau, A New Price Index for the Oldest Securities Market, New York: National Quotation Board, 1948. The insurance index was introduced in 1965 with calculations made back to 1955.
The NQB indices have been tied to the NASDAQ indices to create a longer daily index than NASDAQ provides, and are given using their original numbers. The 35 industrials are given three times a month through September 1948, monthly from October 1948 through February 1949, and daily beginning on March 26, 1949. The Insurance index is daily beginning on February 1, 1965. For the NASDAQ Composite, we have created a composite of the Insurance (30% weight) and Industrials index (70% weight) from February 1, 1965 until February 5, 1971 and used the industrial index alone prior to February 1965. Although the NQB continued to collect this index after 1971, these data have not been included in the database because the NASDAQ indices provided more extensive coverage than the two NQB/OTC indices. The two NQB indices contained the following stocks in 1968:

Industrials: Acme Visible Records, Allyn & Bacon, Inc., American Express Co., American Greetings "A", Anheuser-Busch Inc., Arrow-Hart, Inc., Aztec Oil & Gas, Barnes-Hind Pharmaceuticals, Berkshire Hathaway, Inc., Brush Beryllium, Buckbee-Mears, Cannon Mills, Dun & Bradstreet, Economics Laboratory, Grinnell corporation, Hexcel Corporation, Hoover Company, Hyster Company, Inland Container "A", Kaiser Steel, Kearney & Trecker, Eli Lilly, Magnetics, Mallinckroot Chemical Works "A", Midas International, Nicholson File Co., A.C. Nielson, Noxell Corp, Raychem, O. M. Scott & Sons "A", Tampax Inc., Tecumseh Products, Trico Products, United States Envelope, Will Ross.

Insurance: American General Insurance, American National Insurance, CNA Financial Corp., Combined Insurance Co., Connecticut General Insurance Corp., Crum & Forster, Fidelity Union Life Insurance, Franklin Life Insurance, Hartford Fire Insurance, Jefferson Pilot Corp., Lincoln National Life Insurance, National Life & Accident Insurance, St. Paul Cos., Security life & Trust, U.S. Fidelity & Guaranty Co.

The data for both indices have been adjusted by one day from their original dates. The NQB indices were based on bid-ask spread data from pink sheets. The data were calculated at the end of the day and reported the next day. So the data that were reported for April 2 reflected trading that occurred on April 1. Nasdaq indices, which contain NQB data, have received similar adjustments.
The Nasdaq Composite currently includes over 5,000 companies. The Bank index includes over 350 banks, the Insurance index about 100 companies, and the Other Finance index includes about 620 credit agencies other than banks, including savings and loan associations, securities and commodity brokers, exchanges and dealers, real estate and holdings investment companies not regulated under the Investment Company Act of 1940. The transportation index includes about 90 railroads, trucking companies, airlines, pipelines (except natural gas), services, such as warehousing, and travel arrangements. The telecommunications index includes about 150 telecommunications companies, and the industrial index includes about 3,100 agricultural, mining, construction, manufacturing (electronic components), services, and public administration enterprises.
The base for all the NASDAQ indices is February 5, 1971 = 100 except for the Nasdaq 100 for which the base is January 30, 1985 = 125 and for the Biotech and Computer indices for which the base is November 1, 1993 = 200. The base for the National Market System Indices is July 11, 1984 = 100. All NASDAQ Indices are market value weighted except the NASDAQ-100 Index which is weighted using a modified market capitalization method. The representation of each security in the Index is proportional to its last sale price times the total number of shares outstanding, relative to the total market value of the respective index.

The formula used for determining the Index values is as follows:

Index Level = Current Market Value

Adjusted Base Period Market Value X Base Value

Adjusted Base Period Market Value = Current Market Value After Adjustments

Current Market Value Before Adjustments X Previous Base Period Market Value

The level of an Index will only change as a result of price changes occurring between the opening and closing of the market. Adjustments for securities being added to or deleted from The Nasdaq Stock Market, Inc., or capitalization changes, are adjustments which take place during the system maintenance process which occurs after the market has closed. These adjustments will result in value changes to the current market value and adjusted base period market value, but will not in and of themselves alter the level of an Index.

Stock splits and stock dividends are likewise adjusted for during the system maintenance process. However, the system makes a price adjustment to account for the increased number of shares with the result being that the current market value does not change. As an example, assume that ABC Corp. has 1,000,000 shares outstanding with a last sale price of 20 (market value - $20,000,000) The company has declared a 2 for 1 stock split. During system maintenance on the day prior to the effective date of the split, the system will adjust the shares outstanding to 2,000,000 and will correspondingly adjust the price to 10. Result, the same current market value of $20,000,000.

In the case of cash dividends, no system adjustment is made. Neither the Current Market Value nor the Adjusted Base Period Market Value is adjusted to reflect cash dividends. The index formula relies on market forces to determine the level of the Index.

Name: S&P 500/Cowles Composite Price Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1871 To Jan 1918
Weekly From Jan 1918 To Dec 1927
Daily From Jan 1928 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
For Data before 1871, please see the file GFUS100MPD
After the Dow Jones Averages, the second most historically extensive indices are the Standard and Poor's indices. Whereas the Dow Jones averages were weighted by price, from the beginning, the S&P indices were weighted by capitalization. The original indices were introduced by the Standard Statistics Corporation in 1923 covering 233 stocks in 26 sectors. Data were calculated on a weekly basis back to 1918. The daily indices were introduced in 1928 and consisted of a 90-stock average including 50 industrials, 20 rails and 20 utilities. Data were calculated on a weekly basis back to 1926 and 1927.
The Standard and Poor's Composite combines a number of different indices. From 1791 to 1801, GFD has calculated an equal-weighted index using data from 7 banks (Union National Bank of Boston, Massachusetts National Bank of Boston, the First Bank of the United States, Bank of the State of New York, Bank of Pennsylvania, Bank of South Carolina, and the Bank of America), 3 insurance companies (New York Insurance Company, Insurance Co. of Pennsylvania, Insurance Co. of North America) and two transport companies (Philadelphia and Lancaster Turnpike Company and Schuylkill Permanent Bridge Company).
Using Walter B. Smith and Arthur H. Cole, Fluctuations in American Business, 1790-1860, Cambridge: Harvard Univ. Press, 1935, the index combines the monthly price indexes of Bank stocks (1802-1815, Bank and Insurance Stocks (February 1815-December 1845), and Rails (1834-1862) from Smith and Cole, ibid.: and Railroads (1863-1870) from Frederick R. Macaulay, The Movements of Interest Rates, Bond Yields and Stock Prices in the United States Since 1856, New York: National Bureau of Economic Research, 1938. This data is available in USMACRRM
GFD has used Smitha nd Cole's data on banks from 1802 to 1833. Between 1834 and 1863, the file USCFALLM provides data from Smith and Cole. Beginning in 1871, the Cowles/Standard and Poor's Composite index of stocks is used. The Standard and Poor's indices were first calculated in 1918, and the Cowles Commission back-calculated the series to 1871 using the Commercial and Financial Chronicle. For more information, see Standard and Poor's, Security Price Index Record, New York: Standard and Poor's, 2000 and Cowles Commission for Research in Economics, Common-Stock Indexes, 2nd ed., Bloomington: Principia Press, 1939.
High-low-close are available since January 1930 except for 1/2/41-7/30/46, 2/28/47-3/5/47, 10/24/47-10/28/47, 3/5/48-3/10/48, 5/6/49-5/11/49, 12/23/49-1/23/52, 6/27,30/1952, 9/5,8,9/1952.
The 90-stock Composite was calculated from 1926 through February 1957 when S&P introduced the S&P 500 stock average including 425 industrials, 25 rails and 50 utilities, weighting the index substantially in favor of the industrials. S&P did not calculate the 500-stock index prior to March 1957, but used the old 90-share index (as well as the old 50 industrials, 20 rails and 20 utilities indices) to extend the data back to 1928. The daily closes listed in the Security Price Index Record consist of the 90 stock averages adjusted to the new 1941/43 base from 1926 through February 1957, and the 500 stock averages starting in March 1957. Similarly, the weekly/monthly data for these indices uses the 90 stock average, rather than the more extensive indices of industrials that included 400 stocks, and were calculated on a weekly rather than a daily basis.
The indices were revised again on July 1, 1976 when the rail index was dropped, and was replaced by the Transportation index, and a Financial Index was added. Until that time, financial shares had been excluded from the S&P 500 because many were over-the-counter stocks making it difficult to calculate exact prices for the averages. The components were changed from 425 industrials, 60 utilities and 15 rails to 400 industrials, 40 utilities, 20 transportation and 40 financial stocks in 1976. On April 6, 1988, exact numerical allocations were abandoned allowing the sectoral composition of the S&P 500 index to change as new stocks were removed and added to the S&P 500. Data for the S&P 500 index is theoretical through 1983 and actual, real-time data from January 3, 1984 on.

Where possible, we have included high-low-close data for the indices, which meant readjusting the data for the period prior to March 1957 to the old indices. High-low-close are currently available for 1930-1941, September 1946-December 1949, and beginning in January 1956. Other dates have the close only. The primary sources for these data are Standard Statistics Corp., Base Book, New York: Standard Statistics Corp., 1931, Standard and Poor's Security Price Index Record, New York: Standard and Poor's (1940, 1941, 1948, 1955, 1957, 1962, and biannually since then), Standard and Poor's, Outlook, New York: Standard and Poor's (published weekly) and Standard and Poor's, Statistical Service, New York: S&P. For a detailed history of the components of both the 90 and the 500 stock averages see the current and past issues of the biannual Security Price Index Record published by Standard and Poor's.
The original 500 share indices included 90-95% of the capitalization of the New York Stock Exchange providing the most comprehensive index of stocks then available; however, the rapid expansion in Nasdaq and growth in the NYSE has meant that the S&P indices now represent a smaller proportion of total market capitalization than in the past. The Wilshire 5000, Russell 3000 and Investor's Business Daily 6000 all cover substantially more shares than the S&P 500. Nevertheless, the S&P 500 still represents about 75% of the stock market's capitalization. To update their index, S&P introduced a 400-share Mid-cap index (which was calculated back to 1981), in June 1991, and then introduced a Small Cap 600-share index in October 1994, which was calculated back to December 31, 1993. The 1500-share Supercomposite was introduced in July of 1995 and calculated back to December 31, 1993. In January 2002, S&P introduced the S&P 1000 which includes all the stocks in the S&P 400 Midcap and S&P 600 Small Cap Index. Beginning in March 2004, S&P began adjusting their indices so they would reflect the free float on their stock indices rather than the total capitalization. The free float method reduces the influence of stocks such as Wal-Mart for which 40% of the stock is privately held and not publicly traded.
Volume data are for the stocks traded on the NYSE, not for the S&P 500 stocks.

Name: Hong Kong Hang Seng Composite Index (with GFD Extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Aug 1962 To Nov 1969
Daily From Nov 1969 To Sep 2020
Metadata: The Hang Seng index includes 33 stocks and has a base of July 31, 1964 = 100. Data are monthly through November 1969.  Daily data begin on November 24, 1969. The index was introduced in 1969, and data were calculated back to July 1964 on a monthly basis. The Hang Seng Index is a capitalization-weighted price index, which includes the 33 largest and most liquid stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, using the Laspeyres formula with daily chaining.  Adjustments are made for capitalization and component changes. Monthly data from the Hong Kong Far Eastern Economic Review Index (HKFEERD) has been appended to the Hang Seng Index prior to July 31, 1964.

Name: UK FTSE 100 Index (with GFD Extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Dec 1978 To Dec 1983
Daily From Jan 1984 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The FTSE 100 includes 100 most highly capitalised blue chip companies, representing approximately 80% of the UK market. Bases are 4/10/1962 = 100 for the FTSE All-Share and Non-Financials, 12/31/1983 = 1000 for the FTSE 100, 12/31/1985 = 682.94 for the FTSE 350 indices, 12/31/1985 = 1412.60 for the FTSE 250, 12/31/1992 = 1363.79 for the FTSE Small Cap, 12/30/1994 = 1000 for the FTSE Fledgling and AIM indices, 12/31/1992 = 1000 for the Total Return Indices, and 12/31/1985 = 1000 for all other indices. The FTSE-100 is a capitalization-weighted price index of the 100 largest UK companies by market value, using the Paasche formula, adjusting for capitalization changes, and reviewing components in March, June, September and December. Data are simulated and monthly through 1983 with daily high-low-close beginning in 1984.

Name: UK FTSE All-Share Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jun 1933 To Dec 1964
Weekly From Jan 1965 To Dec 1968
Daily From Dec 1968 To Oct 2020
Metadata: Sources include Thorold Rogers, A History of Prices in England, (1693-1697), Larry Neal, The Rise of Financial Capitalism: International Capital Markets in the Age of Reason, New York: Cambridge Univ. Press, 1990 (1698-January 1811), W. W. Rostow and Anna J. Schwartz, The Growth and Fluctuation of the British Economy 1790-1850), (2 vols.), Oxford: Oxford U.P., 1953, p. 368, (February 1811-December 1850), Hayek as given in Rostow, ibid., p. 456 (January 1851-June 1867), K.C. Smith and G.F. Horne, An Index Number of Securities, 1867-1914, London and Cambridge Economic Service Special Memorandum No. 37, (July 1867-December 1906), Banker's Magazine (January 1907-May 1933), Economist (1933-1962), Financial Times (1950-). Volume data are provided for the London Stock Exchange.  The number of bargains is provided in the FT 30 Industrials file, the Value of shares traded is provided in the FT All-Share Index, and the total shares traded is provided in the FT-500 Non-Financial Index. The All-Share index contains the historical data for the United Kingdom. East Indies Stock is used for 1693.  The index is an unweighted arithmetic average of Bank of England and East Indies stock from 1694 to August 1711, and of Bank of England, East Indies and South Sea stock from September 1711 to January 1811.  Rostow's Total Index of Share Prices is used from 1811 to 1850.  Hayek's index was taken from Rostow and excludes banks, insurance and bridge stocks, but includes industrial stocks.  This index is linked to the London and Cambridge Economic Service index, which begins in July 1867 and continues until 1906.  The L&CES index consisted of 25 stocks in 1867 and had grown to 75 stocks by 1914.   The Banker's Magazine kept a capitalization-weighted index of 287 stocks, which gave the total capital values of the companies that were included.  This was the broadest index of London shares at the time and the index is used beginning in 1907.  Although this index was calculated beginning in 1887, the Banker's Magazine usually omitted calculating the index for one month during the summer, and for this reason it is excluded until 1907 when calculations were made for every month.  The London market closed in August 1914 and reopened in January 1915.  The Banker's Magazine Index is used through May 1933.  Beginning in June 1933, the Actuaries General Index is used.  This index included financial stocks, commodities and utilities, but excluded debentures and preferred shares.   Beginning in April 1962, the Financial Times-Actuaries All-Share Index is used.  All indexes have been chain linked to one another to create a continuous index with the All-Share index's base of April 10, 1962 used as the base for the entire index. The All-Share Index is a capitalization-weighted price index and covers about 98-99% of the capital value of all UK companies.  It uses the Paasche formula, adjust for capitalization changes, and has its components reviewed in December.  It combines the FT-SE 100, FT-SE Mid-250 and FT-SE Small Cap indices, but excludes the Fledgling and AIM index components. Data are weekly from 1965 to 1968 and daily thereafter.

Name: Buenos Aires SE General Index (IVBNG)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1947 To Dec 1966
Daily From Jan 1967 To Oct 2020
Metadata: Data from 1947 to June 1958 uses the Swan, Culbertson and Fritz Index. The index was based upon values from the last Friday of the month for 1938 through 1943, all Fridays for 1944 through 1946, and daily averages from 1947 on. The index included ordinary and preferred shares of 16 companies. Data for 1948-1957 are from a weighted aggregative index with an original base of December 1938 = 100 and was an average of daily closing prices. Data from 1958 to 1965 uses data on Argentine stocks listed in London using the GFD Index calculations converted from GBP to ARS.The Bolsa de Comercio de Buenos Aires introduced a General stock index on December 29, 1966, which is still calculated today. The index includes 15 sector indices for food, banks, insurance, beverages, trade and imports, construction, finance, raw materials, chemicals, manufacturing, metals, paper and printing, utilities, textiles and miscellaneous. The original index can be found in the file ARIVBNGD with the base of December 29, 1966 = 1. Because of Argentina's inflation, two adjustments have been made in the data series for the General Index to make the data more legible.  From 1967 through 1982, the base is December 29, 1977 = 100, from 1983 through 1987, the base is December 29, 1977 = 0.1, and from 1988 on, the base is December 29, 1977 = 0.00001. Data are taken from the Annuario Bursatil, Buenos Aires: Bolsa de Comercio de Buenos Aires. The General Index was revised in 2001 with data recalculated back to June 30, 2000 with June 30, 2000 = 19,570.98. The General Stock Exchange Index (December 30, 1977=0.00001) is based on the quotes of ordinary shares and is used to obtain a wider historical coverage. (The General Stock Exchange Index is adjusted on the basis of the bids and withdrawals of quotes, and the reduction in, or new subscriptions to, the social capital.)

Name: Bombay SE Sensitive Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Annual From Nov 1657 To Jan 1693
Monthly From Feb 1693 To Dec 1945
Weekly From Jan 1946 To Oct 1949
Monthly From Nov 1949 To Mar 1959
Weekly From Apr 1959 To Mar 1961
Monthly From Apr 1961 To Mar 1962
Weekly From Apr 1962 To Mar 1963
Monthly From Apr 1963 To Mar 1964
Weekly From Apr 1964 To Mar 1968
Monthly From Apr 1968 To Apr 1969
Weekly From Apr 1969 To Mar 1970
Monthly From Apr 1970 To Mar 1979
Daily From Apr 1979 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
SENSEX is not only scientifically designed but also based on globally accepted construction and review methodology. First compiled in 1986, SENSEX is a basket of 30 constituent stocks representing a sample of large, liquid and representative companies. The base year of SENSEX is 1978-79 and the base value is 100. The index is widely reported in both domestic and international markets through print as well as electronic media. The Index was initially calculated based on the "Full Market Capitalization" methodology but was shifted to the free-float methodology with effect from September 1, 2003. The "Free-float Market Capitalization" methodology of index construction is regarded as an industry best practice globally. All major index providers like MSCI, FTSE, STOXX, S&P and Dow Jones use the Free-float methodology. Due to is wide acceptance amongst the Indian investors; SENSEX is regarded to be the pulse of the Indian stock market. As the oldest index in the country, it provides the time series data over a fairly long period of time (From 1979 onwards). The initial index for India only provided July data for 1920 and 1921 and was monthly beginning in June 1922. The index had a base of 1914 = 10 and consisted of 102 securities to March 1926 and 99 securities thereafter. The index was discontinued in May 1926. A new index began in April 1927 and was calculated by the magazine Capital from quotations on the Calcutta, Bombay and Madras Stock Exchanges using quotations on the last Tuesday or Wednesday of each month. It was a weighted, geometric average of 11 group indexes. No data are available for June 1940 due to the war. Weekly data from 1946 to 1949 is from Dept. of Research and Statistics Index Numbers of Security Prices, Bombay, 1949 using the All India Variable securities index with a base of 1938 = 100.
Beginning in 1948, the index was compiled by the Office of the Economic Adviser to the Government of India and replaced the previous index. It initially consisted of 86 shares and was based upon middle of the month quotations. The index was an unweighted geometric average of price relatives, adjusted for share dividends and rights based upon daily quotations in Bombay, Calcutta and Madras (and Delhi beginning in 1953). Beginning in April 1979, the Bombay SE Sensitive Index is used since this is the index with the longest series currently available. Data are taken from Statistisches Reichsamt (1920-1926); Reserve Bank of India, Banking and Monetary Statistics of India, Bombay: Reserve Bank of India, 1954, 1962 (1927-1961), UNITED NATIONS (1962-79), Bombay Stock Exchange and Financial Times (1982-) The Bombay SE Sensitive Index (SENSEX) is a capitalization-weighted price index, which includes the 30 leading stocks based on market capitalization and activity in major industries, using the Paasche formula, and adjusting for capitalization and component changes. The index was introduced on January 2, 1986 and calculated back to 1979. Data are daily with HLC from December 1989 until June 1991 and with HLCV from December 1990 until December 1992, except April, May and June of 1992. Although it may appear that there are a large number of daily data missing, this is not the case. Data were obtained from the stock exchange, and the index is complete. During the 1980s, the Bombay stock exchange had the most irregular schedule of any major stock exchange in the world. The base is 1978/1979 = 100.

Name: Santiago SE S&P CLX Indice General de Precios de Acciones
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1894 To Dec 1926
Monthly From Jan 1927 To Dec 1974
Daily From Jan 1975 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The Chilean indices are compiled by the Bolsa de Comercio de Santiago and are published monthly in the Banco Central de Chile Boletin Mensual, Santiago: Banco Central de Chile. Sector indices began in 1927. All other periods are monthly. No data are available from 1975 to 1982 for Shipping and Public Utilities, and from 1981 through 1982 for Insurance and Metallurgy. The Bolsa de Comercio calculates additional subindices, but they are not provided. Indices are calculated on a daily basis, and monthly indices are averages of daily prices. The base for all indices is December 31, 1980 = 100.
For the IGPA index, data from 1894 to 1926 are annual and use an equally weighted composite of ten stocks that were traded on the Santiago Stock Exchange from 1894 when the Bolsa was founded to 1927 when stock market indices were introduced. The 10 shares include 2 banks (Banco de Chile, Banco Hipotecario de Chile), 2 insurance companies (Compania de Seguros America and Compania de Seguros Nacional), 1 mining company (Compania Minera Orura), 2 nitrate companies (Compania Salitera Agua Santa and Compania Salitera Antofagasta), 1 sugar company (Compania Azucarera de Vina del Mar), and two utilities (Compania de Gas de Santiago and Compania de Gas de Valparaiso). Where no quotes were available, the previous year's quote was used. The composite index is used beginning in 1927. The pre-war index was a weighted arithmetic average of price relatives with a moving base, chain linked to the original base, which covered about 25 manufacturing companies. The IGPA general index is used starting in 1960. Data prior to 1975 have been multiplied by 1,000,000 to make the data more legible. The IGPA index is a capitalization-weighted price index that includes the majority of the stocks on the Santiago Stock Exchange, and uses the Paasche formula. The index included 161 stocks in It makes adjustments for capitalization changes and its components are reviewed annually. General Stock Price Index (IGPA) (Base: December 30, 1980) covers the majority of shares listed in the Exchange, classified by sectors according to activity. The index composition is revised once a year.

Name: Ireland ISEQ All-Share Price Index (w/GFD extension)

Weekly From Sep 1820 To May 1821

Metadata: The ISEQ index is the primary index for Ireland today.  This index has been tied to previous stock market indices calculated by the Central Statistical office. The original index was a general, weighted aggregative index, excluding railway shares, and based upon the first of the following month prices.  The index covered around 100 companies on the Dublin Stock Exchange. The original base numbers are preserved in the files IEGEN34M for 1934-1953 with the base January 1936 = 100, and in IEGEN53M for 1953-1988 with the bases 1953 = 100 through 1980 and 1975 = 100 thereafter.   The ISEQ Overall index is used beginning in 1983. The base is January 4, 1988, 9 A.M = 1000 for the Overall, Finance and General Indices. ISEQ has also introduced Small Cap and Information Technology (ITEQ) Indices.  ISEQ calculates both price and return indices. The sources are Central Statistical Office, Statistical Yearbook, (1934-1988) for the two general indices, and the web site of the ISEQ for the data since 1983.  The ISEQ (Irish Stock Exchange Equity Index) Overall share price index measures the change in the prices of ordinary stocks and shares quoted on the Irish Stock Exchange.  Coverage: The ISEQ indices include all domestic and Northern Ireland companies quoted on the Official List and Developing Companies Market equities of the Irish Stock Exchange (78 companies).  Calculation: The index is an arithmetic mean weighted according to the market capitalisation of the company. The national base of the index is 4 January 1988. Monthly data are arithmetic averages of daily closing prices. Annual and quarterly figures are averages of monthly data.

Name: Banca Commerciale Italiana Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Sep 1905 To Dec 1956
Daily From Dec 1956 To Dec 2019
Metadata:
The long-term index begins in September 1905 using the index calculated by Prof. Bachi through December 1930, which consisted of 173 stocks. No data are available for August through December of 1914 due to the war, and data are annual for 1915, 1916, and 1922 through June 1924. Beginning in 1931, Prof. Guarneri's index of 74 stocks is used until June 1939. The index calculated by the Gruppo Edison of 24 shares on the Milan stock exchange is used from 1939 through 1973. It had a base of December 1938 = 100. This index was a weighted aggregative index, adjusted by new capital and share dividends based upon an average of daily quotations in Milan. No datum is available for May 1945. All indices are based upon shares traded on the Milan stock exchange. Sources include La Riforma Sociale (1905-1921), Statistisches Reichsamt (1922-1930); League of Nations (1931-1945), Italian Statistical Institute, Annuario della Congiuntura, Milan: ISI (1946-1949), Banca d'Italia, Bolletino, December 1964, pp. 650-657 (1950-1956), Congiuntura Economica (1956-1972), Banca Commerciale Italiana, Trend of the BCI Indices, Milan: BCI, 1995
The BCI Index data begins on January 3, 1973. To give more historical perspective, the Edison General Index of Italian shares has been appended onto the BCI index to extend the data back to 1956. To get the original data, divide the data by 1.8905 or see the file ITEDGEND. The BCI Index includes over 325 companies listed on the Milan Stock Exchange; it is capitalization-weighted and uses the Paasche formula.

Name: Malaysia KLSE Composite
Periodicity:
Monthly From Nov 1972 To Dec 1979
Daily From Jan 1980 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The sources are Far Eastern Economic Review, Financial Times, Securities Exchange of Singapore, SES Journal, Singapore: SES, Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange, Investors' Digest, Kuala Lumpur: KLSE. The Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange has kept stock indices since 1970. The performance of these indices is very similar to Singapore because many stocks are listed on both exchanges. All of the original indices have a base of December 31, 1969 = 100 except for the Composite whose base is January 3, 1974 = 100. The new indices have a base of December 31, 1990 = 100. See the November 1991 issue of Investor's Digest, page 33 for information on the new indices. For the sub-indices, no data are available for June through August 1985.
The KLSE Composite is a capitalization-weighted price index, using the Laspeyres formula, and adjusting for capitalization changes and component changes. The Composite was introduced on April 4, 1986 and back calculated to 1974.

Name: Austria Trading Index (ATX)
Periodicity: Daily From Jan 1986 To Oct 2020
Metadata: At the foundation of the Austrian Futures and Options Exchange (Ã–TOB) the Austrian Traded Index was constituted to fulfill both the descriptive and the operative functions of a representative stock market index. As an aggregate market indicator the ATX documents the price dynamics of the most liquid market segment of Austrian stocks which represents about 77% of total stock market turnover and about 52% of total market capitalization at the end of April 1995 (Austrian Options and Futures Exchange, 1995a). Simultaneously, it also serves as an underlying for futures and options contracts.       Since November 1995, the ATX is the core of the newly established ATX-family which comprises the ATX, the ATX 50, the ATX 50 Performance Index (ATX 50P), and the ATX-MidCap (Austrian Futures and Options Exchange, 1995b). Pursuing the intention to offer a benchmark for investment funds, the Ã–TOB sampled the ATX 50 and the ATX 50P so as to represent the portfolio of all investible Austrian stocks. Both indexes cover the ATX stocks plus the succeeding most attractive stocks. The 50 stocks included in the indexes represent 81% of the total capitalization of the official market segment and 97% of total stock market turnover. In the case of the ATX 50P dividends are assumed to be reinvested in the entire sample of index stocks so that the weight of each stock remains the same as in the ATX 50 (Austrian Association of Financial Analysts, 1996). The ATX-MidCap index sample consists of the ATX 50 sample minus the ATX sample minus all stocks with a market capitalization exceeding ATS 7.5 bill.       Regarding its construction principle, the ATX and the other members of the index family belong to the category of capitalization-weighted value ratios with daily chaining. Note that the market capitalization is corrected by a free float factor, which is intended to ensure that the weight of a particular title in the ATX corresponds to the amount of capital actually available for public trading on the stock exchange. The selection of the index sample is carried out according to the following three criteria:     Liquidity    All stocks that are included in the index must be listed in the official market segment of continuously traded stocks;         Market capitalization    Eligible stocks must belong to the stocks with the largest market capitalization on the Vienna Stock Exchange;         Free floating capital      A sufficiently large free floating capital is required for a stock to be included in the ATX. The number of outstanding shares taken into account for calculating the weight of each stock in the index is lowered by a flat rate of 50% if the free floating capital is less than 25% of the total outstanding capital of the respective stock.     Since the ATX is intended to reflect all price changes caused by market fluctuations, the index is adjusted for technical price changes except for those due to dividend payments. If a stock is suspended from trading the last available price is used for calculating the index.       Documenting a period of highly volatile trading on the Vienna Stock Exchange, one year and eight months after its official launching the ATX fell to its historic low of 682.96 index points on August 13, 1992.       References:    Austrian Association of Financial Analysts (1996): Jahrbuch 1995 (Yearbook 1995), Sparkassenverlag: Vienna.    Austrian Futures and Options Exchange (1995a): ATX Austrian Traded Index, member information series, Austrian Futures and Options Exchange (Ã–TOB) : Vienna.    Austrian Futures and Options Exchange (1995b): Die ATX-Indexfamilie, documentation series, Austrian Futures and Options Exchange (Ã–TOB): Vienna.    GrÃ¼nbichler, A. (1991): Der Austrian Traded Index (ATX) im Vergleich mit internationalen Aktienindices, Ã–sterreichisches BankArchiv, vol. 39, pp. 432-441.     The ATX indices are optionable indices that include shares traded on the Vienna Stock Exchange.  The ATX includes the 22 most active stocks on the Vienna SE; the ATX Midcap includes the next 26 capitalization stocks after the ATX-22, and the ATX-50 includes the 50 largest capitalization shares representing 87% of capitalization and 94% of turnover traded on the “fliesshandel” (main market). The Performance Index is based upon the ATX-50 Shares.  The bases for the indices are January 2, 1991 = 1000 for the ATX, October 31, 1995 = 308.33 for the ATX Midcap (1/3 of the ATX on that date) and October 31, 1995 = 462.49 for the ATX-50 (1/2 of the ATX on that date).The Vienna Stock Exchange revised their indices in 1980 and calculated the new sector indices back to December 1967.  The base for the General Index (Wiener Borsekammer) is December 31, 1967 = 100; January 2, 1991 = 1000 for the ATX; October 31, 1995 = 308.33 for the ATX Midcap (1/3 of the ATX on that date); and October 31, 1995 = 462.49 for the ATX-50 (1/2 of the ATX on that date). On January 1,2002, the ATX reformed their indices because the ATX was separated into two markets: the Prime Market and the Standard Market.  The ATX (Austrian Traded Index) covers 20 stocks of the Prime Market with the highest liquidity and market capitalization (1991=1000).

Name: Austria Wiener Boersekammer Share Index (WBKI)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1922 To Aug 1985
Daily From Aug 1985 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The Wiener Borsekammer Index (WBKI) includes historical data series for Vienna. Volume is provided for 1/22-5/39, 11/59-12/64, and 10/66 on. Data were taken from Statistisches Reichsamt Statistische Nachrichten,(1921-1924), Institute fur Konjunkturforschung (1925-1938); Vienna Statistical Yearbook (1943-1945), and Statistisches Nachrichten (1946-). The Vienna Stock Exchange was closed in July 1914 and reopened on March 14, 1916. The data starting in 1922 are from a general index of stocks on the Vienna Stock Exchange taken from the Statistische Nachrichten.
An index of 21 industrial shares calculated by the Institut fur Konjunkturforschung is used from 1925 until 1928, and an index of 34 industrial shares from January 1929 to June 1939. No data are available for October 1931, April 1938, July 1939 until 1942, and April 1945 to March 1946. The Central Statistical Office Index is used through 1951. It included 18 shares through October 1946, 19 shares through August 1947, and 23 shares thereafter. Beginning in 1952, an index of 42 shares which was calculated by the Institute of Economic Research is used which was an unweighted arithmetic average of prime relatives with a base of March 1938 = 100 which included 36 industrial and 6 bank shares. In 1954 shares of nationalized enterprises were replaced by private enterprises. This index is used until December 1967 when the Wiener Borsekammer index is substituted for it.
In 1980 the old indices calculated by the Vienna Stock Exchange were replaced with new indices which were rebased to December 31, 1967 = 100. The index is capitalization-weighted and includes all domestic Official Market shares. The index uses the Paasche formula, and adjusts for capitalization changes and component changes. It has been calculated on a daily basis since September 2, 1985.
The ATX indices are optionable indices that include shares traded on the Vienna Stock Exchange. The ATX includes the 22 most active stocks on the Vienna SE; the ATX Midcap includes the next 26 capitalization stocks after the ATX-22, and the ATX-50 includes the 50 largest capitalization shares representing 87% of capitalization and 94% of turnover traded on the “fliesshandel” (main market). The Performance Index is based upon the ATX-50 Shares. The bases for the indices are January 2, 1991 = 1000 for the ATX, October 31, 1995 = 308.33 for the ATX Midcap (1/3 of the ATX on that date) and October 31, 1995 = 462.49 for the ATX-50 (1/2 of the ATX on that date).
Definition: The Vienna Stock Exchange WBI (Wiener Borse Index) share index relates to all Official Market shares quoted on the spot market and thus reflect movements on the Austrian stock market as a whole.
Coverage: The Official Market is the largest and most important segment of the exchange dealing with securities of high trading volumes, warrants and almost all bonds (currently over 100 stocks are traded). Criteria for admission to the Official Market relate to a specified minimum nominal value of the company's shares, to a three year financial history of the company and to a lack of any buying restrictions on trading in the company's shares, to the number of 'free' shares available for trading, etc. Foreign registered companies and investment funds are not included.
Collection: The index is compiled and published by the Vienna Stock Exchange and is available on the Internet.
Calculation: The index is an arithmetic mean, weighted according to the market capitalisation of the company and calculated at closing prices using the Paasche formula. Monthly figures refer to the middle of the month. Annual and quarterly data are averages of monthly figures. The index is based 31 December 1967 = 100.

Name: Tel Aviv SE 125 Broad Index

Metadata: The Tel Aviv 125 Index is a capitalization-weighted index of 125 stocks traded on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange (TASE). The Index was developed with a base value of 100 as of December 31, 1991. The number of stocks was increased from 100 to 125 on February 9, 2017.

Name: Amsterdam AEX Stock Index
Periodicity: Daily From Jan 1983 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The AEX includes 20 leading Dutch stocks that trade on the Amsterdam Stock Exchange and together represent approximately 80 percent of the total market value of all shares listed on the ASE. The index assumes an equal investment in each of the 20 stocks in 1983 and uses the Paasche formula to calculate its values. When the Euro was introduced on January 1, 1999, the AEX index was divided by 2.20371. The AEX-index is a weighted index based on the prices of shares in 25 leading companies listed on Euronext Amsterdam. It is the best-known index of Euronext Amsterdam made up of the 25 most active securities in the Netherlands. This index provides a fair representation of the Dutch economy.
The AEX-index does not cover investment trust, holding companies for securities listed on Euronext Amsterdam, securities subject to a special listing regime, securities listed less than eighty trading days, securities listed on Euronext Amsterdam in the foreign shares category, and other securities, companies or institutions as determined by the compiler. Decision on this last category depends on the tradability (frequency) and the settlement (the extent to which short positions can be taken and settled) of the securities.
The AEX All Shares Index measures the changes in prices of shares quoted on the Amsterdam Stock Exchange.
Calculation: Daily indices are calculated as the arithmetic mean of individual prices weighted according to the market capitalisation of the company at the current value. Adjustments are made when necessary to take account of capital changes in the weighting pattern. No adjustment is made in respect of share price changes due to dividend payments. The base of the index is 31 December 1983=100.

Name: India NSE-50 Index
Periodicity: Daily From Jul 1990 To Oct 2020
Metadata: S&P CNX Nifty is a well diversified 50 stock index accounting for 23 sectors of the economy. It is used for a variety of purposes such as benchmarking fund portfolios, index based derivatives and index funds.

Name: Mumbai (Bombay) Stock Exchange 100 Index
Periodicity:
Monthly From Apr 1984 To Dec 1986
Weekly From Jan 1987 To Mar 1989
Daily From Mar 1989 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
For the BSE-100, data are monthly through 1986, weekly in 1987 and daily thereafter. The BSE National Index is a capitalization-weighted price index including the 100 stocks based on market activity on the 5 major Indian stock exchanges. It includes major industries and the BSE 30 Sensitive shares, uses the Paasche formula, and adjusts for capitalization changes and component changes. Selection depends upon market activity, due representation to various industry groups, and representation of trading activity on major exchanges. The index was compiled beginning on January 3, 1989. A need was felt for a more broad-based index, which can also reflect the movement of stock prices on a national scale because the BSE Sensitive Index has only 30 scrips. Bombay Stock Exchange Limited, started compilation and publication of an index series called "BSE National Index" since 3rd January, 1989.

Coverage : The equity shares of 100 companies from the "Specified" and the "Non-Specified" list of the five major stock exchanges, viz. Mumbai, Calcutta, Delhi, Ahmedabad and Madras have been selected for the purpose of compiling the BSE National Index. The criteria for selection had been market activity, due representation to various industry-groups and representation of trading activity on major stock exchanges.

Base-Year : The financial year 1983-84 has been chosen as the base year. The price stability during that year and proximity to the index series were the main consideration for choice of 1983-84 as the base year.

Method of Compilation : The basic method of compilation is the same as the one used in the case of the BSE Sensitive Index. However, in the case of BSE National Index, a distinction is made between "local scrips" for which prices were taken from only one exchange and "Inter-Exchange scrips" for which an average of the prices quoted on two or more exchanges were considered for index compilation.

Designation of the BSE 100 National Index to the BSE 100 Index
As noted above, the BSE 100 National index used to take prices of certain scrips from other exchanges or weighted average of some scrips which were popular on other exchanges in order to reflect market movements at the national level. However, changes in trading technology, longer trading period and almost instantaneous availability of information across the country have ensured that there is little or no difference in prices of the index scrips. Therefore, the Exchange administration has decided to redesignate the BSE 100 National index as the 'BSE 100' index. Since October 14, 1996, the prices of the BSE are taken to calculate the index.

Shifting of BSE-100 Index to Free-Float Methodology of Index maintenance:
In line with the shift of the BSE Indices to the globally accepted Free-Float methodology, BSE-100 was shifted to Free-Float methodology effective from April 5th, 2004. The method of computaion of Free-Float Index and determination of Free-Float Factors is similar to the methodology described in SENSEX.

Name: Nigeria SE All-Share Index
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1984 To Dec 1987
Monthly From Jan 1988 To Nov 1988
Daily From Nov 1988 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The Lagos Stock Exchange Index is used. Data are annual for 1984 through 1987, monthly beginning in 1988, and daily beginning on November 14, 1988. The Nigerian Stock Exchange is the third largest stock exchange in Africa. The stock exchange was established in 1960 and has some 180 listed companies. All listings are included in the only index, the Nigerian Stock Exchange All Shares Index. The main drawback of the Exchange is the absence of Nigeria's 10 largest, government-owned companies on the stock exchange list. The base is December 31, 1984 = 100. The Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) was established in 1960 as the Lagos Stock Exchange.  In December 1977, it became the NSE with six branches established in some of the major commercial cities. Each branch has a trading floor, of which three are electronic. The Exchange started operations in Lagos in 1961 with 19 securities listed for trading. Today there are 260 securities listed on the Exchange, made up of 17 Government Stocks, 49 Industrial Loan (Debenture/Preference) Stocks and 194 Equity /Ordinary Shares of companies, all with a total market capitalization of approximately N615.7 billion.

Name: Brussels All-Share Price Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1870 To Dec 1896
Monthly From Jan 1897 To Dec 1984
Daily From Jan 1985 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The Spot Index includes the long-term historical data for Belgium's stock market.  No data are available from 1914 to 1918.  Data for 1919 to 1925 uses a quarterly index calculated by the Moniteur des Interets Materiels.  Beginning in 1926, a monthly index of 80 industrial shares calculated by the National Bank of Belgium is used.  No data are available for June to November 1940 and from August 1944 to May 1945 when the stock market was closed in Belgium due to the war.  The post-war index was a weighted, arithmetic average of price relatives with moving base, chain-linked to 1953 = 100.  The index was weighted by the market value of shares of all companies included at the beginning of the month in Brussels and Antwerp, omitting in the calculation for any period shares of companies changing their capitalization during the period. This index was an all-share index consisting of 400-500 shares that was calculated at the beginning of each month. The current Brussels SE Price Index was introduced in 1985 and calculated back to the base of December 31, 1979. It includes all shares traded on the Brussels Stock Exchange. Monthly volume begins in December 1940. Sources for the index include: Bulletin Trimestriel de l'Institut des Sciences Economiques, December 1929, p. 34 (1897-1913), International Statistics Institute (1919-1936), League of Nations (1937-1940), Institut National de Statistique, Bulletin de Statistique Brussels: INS (1940-79), Brussels Stock Exchange (1980-). The BAS index is an "All shares" index representing the evolution of the Euronext Brussels Market as a whole. The Index is based on the closing prices of all belgian shares listed on the fixing and continuous segment, of the First and the Second Market. The shares are weighted according to their daily market capitalisation. However, companies having a free float of 5% or less will be taken out of the index with free float being a measure ( in %) for the part of the issued shares of the company that are available to the public for trading.The BAS index has two versions, Price and Return. The basis of both the Price and Return Index is 01.01.1980 = 1000. The indexes are calculated once a day at the closing of the market and are published after 5.40 pm. The only difference between a Price Index and a Return Index is that the price index does not take into account the reinvestment of NET dividends.

Name: Korea SE Stock Price Index (KOSPI)
Periodicity: Daily From Jan 1962 To Sep 2020
Metadata:
The Korean Stock Exchange was founded as the non-profit Daehan Stock Exchange in February 1956, reorganized as a corporation with the enactment of the Securities and Exchange Act of 1962. The stock exchange was closed on February 26, 1963 because of a stock market crisis. The market reopened on May 5, 1963 as the Korea Stock Exchange.
South Korea's stock exchange maintains about 20 sector indices and another 15 sub-indices. The 20 primary sector indices are provided here. Data are HLC through 1989 and monthly closes thereafter. The primary sources for these data are Korea Stock Exchange, Korea Composite Stock Price Index, Seoul: KSE, 1991, and Korea Stock Exchange, Monthly Key Statistics, Korea: The Exchange (1990-). The base for the general indices is January 4, 1980 = 100 and the base for the KOSPI 200 indices is January 3, 1990 = 100. The index included 50 shares from 1972 to 1974, and is an all-share index starting in 1975. The 1972 to 1974 data have been adjusted to link it to the Composite Index. To get the original data, multiply the data by 1.5223. This is a capitalization-weighted price index including all stocks listed on the Seoul Stock Exchange, using the Paasche formula, and adjusting for capitalization and component changes. There is a manufacturing index, 34 industrial sub-indices, and 3 indices based on capitalization. Historically, because stocks go ex-dividend on the first trading day of the year, the index can drop by as much as 10% on that day. Share volume is included in the volume column and the value of shares traded is included in the open interest column. The base is January 4, 1980 = 100. In November 2000, the Korea Stock Exchange discontinued a number of minor sector indices. Sources are Fact Book, Seoul: Korea Stock Exchange and Korea Stock Exchange, Monthly Key Statistics, Korea: The Exchange (1970-) and Bank of Korea, Monthly Statistical Review, Seoul: Bank of Korea.

Name: Istanbul SE IMKB-100 Price Index
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1986 To Feb 1986
Weekly From Feb 1986 To Oct 1987
Daily From Oct 1987 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The Istanbul Menkul Krymetler Borsas (IMKB) index was calculated weekly until October 26, 1987 and daily thereafter, and has been calculated on a capitalization-weighted basis since the end of 1990. It is a float capitalization-weighted price index that includes stocks based upon high capitalization and daily average trading volume, which have been incorporated for at least three years.  The index uses the Paasche formula with adjustment for capitalization changes and float. Its components are reviewed in January and July. The index included 77 industrials and 20 financials in 1995. On January 1, 1997, the Istanbul Composite was renamed the IMKB National 100 Index and its value was divided by 100.  The ISE-100 monitors share prices of 100 companies traded on the National Market of the Istanbul Stock Exchange. Dividend yields are not included. It is designed to give a comprehensive measure of the market's performance.  Coverage: The index is compiled from share prices of a sample of 75 companies, which represent at least 85% of all the quoted stock market companies and account for 93.3% of the total market capitalisation. The index composition is reviewed every trois months on the basis of market capitalisation and liquidity.  Calculation: Data are weighted arithmetic means of closing prices in Turkish lira are taken. Weights are according to flotation (i.e. the portion of the capital sold to the public). The national base is January 1986=100.

Name: Athens SE General Index (w/GFD extension)

Monthly From Jan 1954 To Sep 1988
Daily From Oct 1988 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The pre-war index was calculated by the Bank of Greece and included 7 industrial stocks through 1937 and 26 stocks thereafter. No data are available from October 1931 until November 1932 when the stock market was closed, and from October 1940 until December 1951. Data are annual for 1928 and the source is The Greek government’s Annuaire Statistique (1928-1940).
The National Bank of Greece kept indicators of several sectors for the Athens Stock Exchange. These data were published both in Greece's monthly statistical publication and the National Bank of Greece's monthly publication. The indices were revised in 1980 when a general index was introduced. Data are annual for 1952-53 and monthly thereafter, except for indices beginning in 1978, which are annual from January 1978 through September 1979 and monthly thereafter. The indices were discontinued at the end of 1996 and their base was 1978 = 100. The index was based upon industrial shares from 1929 to 1979, and upon all shares starting in 1980. No index was calculated in August 1974 due to the political problems stemming from the Turkish invasion of Cyprus. The ASE General Index is used beginning in December 1986. The sources for this data are Bank of Greece, Trapeza tes Hellado (Report), Athens (1952-96), Marcel Garneau, World Directory of Stock Exchanges, W.I.S.E.R. Research, 1993 (1986-93), Athens Stock Exchange (1990-). On March 1, 2001, the Athens SE introduced new industries to conform with the GICS standards established by S&P and Morgan Stanley. Beginning on December 31, 2005, the index was calculated by FTSE.
The composite price index of the ATHEX, comprises the 60 most highly capitalized shares of the main market and reflects general trends of the stock market.

Name: Oslo SE OBX-25 Stock Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1914 To Oct 1991
Daily From Oct 1991 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The OBX Index consists of the 25 most traded securities in the OSEBX Index. The constituents are selected on the basis of six months turnover rating. It is a semiannually revised free float adjusted price index (not dividend adjusted) with composition changes implemented on the third Friday in December and June. In the period between the composition review dates the number of shares for each constituent is fixed with exception of continuous adjustments for corporate actions with priority for excisting shareholders. The OBX Index is a tradeable index with exchange traded futures and options avaliable. The OBX Index includes industrial, banking and whaling/shipping shares from 1918 to date. No data are available for April and May 1940 due to the war. The index was calculated by the Central Bureau of Statistics a weighted geometric average of price relatives, weighted according to the approximate paid-up capital of the companies included, omitting in the calculation for any period, shares of companies changing their capitalization during the period. About 50 shares were included in the index. Weights were adjusted only when large changes in paid-up capital of a company occurred. Mid-month prices in Oslo were used. When the indices were revised in 1983, return indices replaced the price indices. Therefore, MSCI's price index is used from 1983 to 1989 and the OBX from December 1990 on. Sources include Statistisk Sentralbyra, Statistisk Arbok, Oslo: Statistisk Sentralbyra and Statistisk Sentralbyra, Statistisk Manedshefte and Statistiske Meldinger, Oslo: Statistisk Sentralbyra (1918-).
The Oslo SE indices are capitalization-weighted total return indices that include all domestic companies on the main list, using Paasche formula with chaining. Adjustment is made for capitalization changes, component changes and dividend payments. The SMBX index includes only small businesses. The OBX Stock Index is a capitalization-weighted price index that includes the 25 most traded shares during the previous six months, using the Paasche formula with chaining. Components are reviewed twice a year, and it has a base of January 1, 1987 = 200.
