Name: Jakarta SE Composite Index
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1977 To Mar 1983
Daily From Apr 1983 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The Jakarta SE Index is a capitalization-weighted price index including all listed stocks on the Jakarta Stock Exchange and uses a Paasche formula. The index was introduced in 1982 when 13 shares were traded, and backdated to December 31, 1977 when one share was traded on the exchange. The index is calculated as the sum of the regular closing price multiplied by number of shares and divided by base value. The first CSPI base value of 100 was August 10, 1982 with 25 issuers, which included the weighted capital of all listed stock, not issued stock. The latest base value of August 14, 1991 = 100 covers 132 issuers divided into 10 economic sectors. The 132 issuers cover all companies whose shares are traded on the JSX.

In calculating the CSPI, base prices and values are adjusted for bonus and rights issues, and for share splits and consolidations. The base price for new listed companies is the IPO price.

Name: New Zealand SE All-Share Capital Index
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1862 To Jan 1970
Daily From Jan 1970 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The NZSX All Index comprises all domestic equity securities listed on the NZSX Market. Constituents are weighted by free float market capitalisation. Data refer to the "Capital" (price) component of New Zealand Exchange Limited's NZSX All index. It measures movements in the capital value of all securities traded on the exchange, i.e. excluding payments to shareholders.  Coverage: The index relates to the equity securities of all listed companies (150 in total). Equity securities are generally those carrying a right to vote or to participate in the assets of the company, or those which may be converted into securities having such voting or participation rights. Fixed interest securities and overseas listed issuers are excluded.  Collection: The New Zealand Exchange Limited compiles and publishes the data.  Calculation: Monthly figures are end-of period. Quarterly and annual figures are the averages of monthly data.

Name: Paris CAC-40 Index
Periodicity: Daily From Jul 1987 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The CAC 40 index is the main benchmark for Euronext Paris. Tracking a sample of Blue Chip stocks, its performance is closely correlated to that of the market as a whole. The index contains 40 stocks selected among the top 100 market capitalization and the most active stocks listed on Euronext Paris, and is the underlying asset for options and futures contracts. The base value is 1 000 at December 31, 1987. The Expert Commission indices committee decided that the CAC 40 index will shift to free-float weightings from December 1 2003. This is in keeping with the general trend for major market indices and the CAC 40 weightings will be based on free float capitalisation instead of total market capitalisation. Free float will be reassessed once a year on the basis of information then publicly available, and will systematically be rounded up to the nearest multiple of 5%. It may also be adjusted at other dates in the event of a transaction or transactions reducing or increasing free float by five percentage points or more. The weighting of any one stock in the CAC 40 index will be capped at 15%, ensuring that no single stock carries too much weight and that the sample remains representative.    The CAC-40 Index is a capitalization-weighted price index of the 40 largest stocks by capitalization and liquidity on the official list, using the Paasche formula, and adjusting for capitalization and component changes. In 1995, the index included 20 Industrial, 9 Service and 11 Financial shares. HLC are included beginning in August 1991. This is an index of the 40 most actively traded shares on the Paris stock exchange. The base is December 31, 1987 = 1000.

Name: Switzerland Price Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Annual From Dec 1899 To Dec 1913
Monthly From Jan 1914 To Dec 1937
Weekly From Jan 1938 To Jan 1969
Daily From Jan 1969 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
An index of 21 stocks calculated by the Swiss National Bank is used from 1910 to 1925 when a broader index of stocks was introduced. The Swiss National Bank (Schweizerisches Nationalbank) published weekly indices of Swiss stocks for 12 different sectors from the 1920s until they were discontinued in 1988 when they were replaced by the Switzerland Performance Indices. Data are monthly through 1937, semi-monthly through 1955, and weekly thereafter.
The Swiss Bankcorp indices were discontinued in 1997. The SBC indices included over 400 stocks traded on the Zurich, Geneva and Basle exchanges. SBC calculated a general index and 11 sector indices. Each of these 12 indices had three separate indices for all shares, for bearer shares and for registered shares. In addition to this, SBC calculated price indices that were capitalization-weighted using the Laspeyres formula and omitting dividends, and SBC calculated total-return performance indices. This created a total of 72 (12x3x2) indices. The price indices had a base of December 31, 1958 = 100 and the performance indices hade a base of April 1, 1987 = 1000. Where possible, data from the Swiss National Bank indices have been added to provide more historical data. The primary sources for these data are Statistischen Bureau, Statistisches Jahrbuch der Schweiz, Bern: Verlag des Ar. Institut Orell Fussli (1920-1965) and Schweizerisches Nationalbank, Monatsbericht, Zurich. The Swiss Bankcorp sector indices were used since they were the broadest indices with the longest series of historical data.
The Vereinigung Schweizerischer Effektenborsen calculates indices for shares traded on the Swiss Stock Exchanges. Both price and return indices are calculated. The base is January 6, 1987 = 1000 for the return indices and January 6, 1987 = 100 for the price indices. Where possible, the SPI price indices have been combined with the Swiss Bankcorp and Swiss National Bank indices to provide more complete series. Data are monthly through 1937, semi-monthly through 1955, and weekly thereafter.

Name: Nasdaq 100 Index
Periodicity: Daily From Jan 1985 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The NASDAQ-100 Index includes 100 of the largest domestic and international non-financial companies listed on The Nasdaq Stock Market based on market capitalization. The Index reflects companies across major industry groups including computer hardware and software, telecommunications, retail/wholesale trade and biotechnology. It does not contain financial companies including investment companies. The NASDAQ-100 Index is calculated under a modified capitalization-weighted methodology.

On January 31, 1985, the NASDAQ-100 Index began with a base of 250.00. On January 1, 1994, the NASDAQ-100 base was reset by division of a factor of 2.00 to 125.00.

Name: Tel Aviv All-Share Price Index
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1949 To Dec 1966
Daily From Dec 1966 To Jun 1975
Monthly From Jul 1975 To Jun 1981
Daily From Jun 1981 To Jul 2007
Monthly From Jul 2007 To Jun 2010
Daily From Jul 2010 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The original Israel indices included indices for government securities, debentures, preferred, ordinary shares and a general index.  In 1962, the index, base (from 1950 to 1960), and method of calculation were changed. In 1966 a daily index and sector indices were introduced.  The Ordinary Share Index is used through 1966, and the General Index of Share Prices is used from 1966 on. These are continuous chain-linked indices of shares traded on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange. The Maof Index covers the 25 largest capitalization shares on the Tel Aviv stock exchange, and the Mishtanim index is a bilateral index of 100 shares. The General Index is a continuous chain-linked index of all shares and convertibles traded on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange. Warrants are excluded.  The historical data has been linked to both the General Index and the Mishtamin-100 index.  Data have been multiplied by 1000 prior to 1980 to make the data more readable.  Sources for the data include ï¿½Securities' Price Index,ï¿½ Statistical Bulletin of Israel, Vol. III, No. 4-5, October 1952-April 1953, pp. LVII-LVIII, Israel Statistical Bulletin of Israel (1949-), Technical Publication No. 13, 1963 (Hebrew), Supplement to the Monthly Bulletin of Statistics, No. 2, 1977

Name: Australia S&P/ASX 200 Composite
Periodicity:
Monthly From Dec 1979 To May 1992
Daily From Jun 1992 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The S&P/ASX 200 index is recognised as the investable benchmark for the Australian equity market. It addresses the needs of investment managers to benchmark against a portfolio characterized by sufficient size and liquidity. The S&P/ASX 200 is comprised of the S&P/ASX 100 plus an additional 100 stocks. It forms the basis for the ASX mini200 futures contract, and the streetTRACKS S&P/ASX 200 exchange-traded fund. The S&P/ASX 200 represented approximately 90% of the total market capitalisation of the Australian market at June 30, 2002.   Australia revised their indices in April 2000. The ASX, in association with S&P, introduced new indices based upon the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS). Before then, liquidity requirements had kept some shares out of the All Ordinaries index, but the ASX removed the liquidity requirements to expand the number of stocks that were included.  This allowed the ASX All-Ordinaries index to expand to 500 companies.  Three new indices were introduced, the ASX 300 which includes the top 300 capitalization stocks, the ASX 200 which includes the top 200 capitalization stocks, and the ASX Small Ordinaries which includes the 200 largest capitalization stocks after the ASX 100.  The ASX 20, ASX 50 and ASX 100 indices were maintained and sector indices were introduced for the ASX 200 indices. The base for the S&P/ASX 200 and S&P/ASX 300 sector indices is March 31, 2000 = 3133.3 for the price indices and March 31, 2000 = 14690 for the accumulation indices. Data were calculated back to March 31, 2000, and where possible, we have used historical ASX index data to extend the indices further back.

Name: Dow Jones Composite Average (Actual)
Periodicity: Daily From Nov 1933 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The Dow Jones Composite offers an interesting contrast to the S&P Composite due to the different weights.  Industrials make up 80% of the stocks in the S&P Composite, but less than 50% of the Dow Jones Composite.  Consequently, the similarities in movement between the Dow Jones Composite and the Dow Jones Industrials are much smaller than the similarities between the S&P Composite and the S&P Industrials.  The DJCA originally had 70 stocks in it because the Utilities had 20 stocks in it until it was reorganized to include only electric utilities rather than all types of utilities including telephones, and to exclude holding companies.  The Dow Jones Composite Average has been composed of 65 stocks since June 2, 1938.

Name: OMX Copenhagen All-Share Price Index
Periodicity:
Monthly From Jan 1873 To Jan 1979
Daily From Jan 1979 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
KAX is the Exchange's all-share index. On 15 June 2001, KAX replaced the previous all-share index. The switch to KAX was made at the same time as the equity market adopted the GICS model (Global Industry Classification Standard) developed by Morgan Stanley and Standard & Poor's.The KAX all-share index started with the base number of 100.00 on 31 December 1995. KAX is here calculated as a price index.
Global Financial Data collected share price data on individual companies that was provided in Statistiske Department, Statistisk Arbog, Copenhagen: Statistiske Dept. from 1873 to 1920 and calculated a cap-weighted index based upon the shares that traded on the Copenhagen Stock Exchange.
Denmark introduced stock exchange indices in 1921 with data calculated back to 1914. The data are taken from the Statistiske Efterretninger for and from the Statistiske Department, Statistisk Arbog, Copenhagen: Statistiske Dept. Two primary revisions have occurred in the indices. The first occurred in 1960 when several new indices were introduced. Information on these changes can be found in “Nyt Aktiindeks,” Statistiske Efterretninger, Vol. 52, No. 52 (1960): 795-797. The second revision came in 1983 when several financial indices were introduced. Data are annual averages for 1914 through 1920 and monthly thereafter. The base for the current indices is January 1, 1983 = 100 through 2001.
On June 15, 2001, the Copenhagen Stock Exchange introduced new indices. The CSE adopted the GICS (Global Industry Classification Standard) system developed by Morgan Stanley and Standard and Poor's. The base for the new indices was set at December 31, 1995 = 100. The following indices are currently calculated by the CSE. For the main index, data are annual from 1914 through 1920 and monthly thereafter. The Copenhagen Stock Exchange was closed between September 20, 1931 and October 14, 1931. No data are available for May 1940 because the stock market was closed from April 9 to June 5, 1940 and from September 1-11, 1940. The pre-war index was a weighted arithmetic average of price relatives, weighted by value of shares outstanding, adjusted for new capital, share dividends and rights. The average of the monthly high and low quotations in Copenhagen was used to calculate the index value. The index covered about 20 companies, which represented 60% of the share capital of industrial companies on the exchange. The indices underwent major revisions in 1960 and in 1983. Historical data is taken from Statistiske Department, Statistisk Arbog and Statistiske Efternetringer, Copenhagen: Statistiske Dept. (1916-1984).
The Copenhagen SE index is a capitalization-weighted price index of all shares excluding foreign companies, mutual funds and two holding companies (EAC-Holding and GN Store Nord Holding), using the Paasche formula and adjusting for capitalization and component changes. Data before 1983 have been adjusted to the new base. The KFX-20 index includes the 20 most liquid shares traded on the Copenhagen stock exchange. The old Midcap Index was discontinued in March 2000 and replaced by the KFMX index. The old index has been spliced onto the new index to give a more continuous series.
The KAX includes all shares traded on the CSE, and the KBX is a Benchmark investible index that is free float adjusted. The KBX is weighted by the number of shares accessible to investors rather than the number of shares outstanding. The KBX is revised on January 1 and July 1 of each year.

Name: FTSE/JSE All-Share Index (w/GFD extension)
Periodicity:
Monthly From Feb 1834 To May 1986
Daily From May 1986 To Oct 2020
Metadata:
The monthly indices are calculated by the Reserve Bank of South Africa for the Stock Exchange of Johannesburg and are reported in the Monthly Review. Indices are provided for share prices, price/earning ratios and for stock yields. The source for data prior to 1947 is from C. G. W. Schumann and A. E. Scheurkogel, Industrial and Commercial Share Price Indices in South Africa, Stellenbosch: Bureau for Economic Research, 1947. All post-1947 monthly data come from the Reserve Bank of South Africa's monthly publication. Data are for the Overall index through 1995 and the All-Share index thereafter. Data from the GFD Indices is used from 1834 until 1909.
The Overall index from 1910 through 1959 is weighted 50% in the GFD Indices and 50% in industrial and commercial shares (See _JIAID). The pre-1960 industrials index included industrial and commercial shares. The index was a weighted arithmetic average of price relatives, weighted by the average market value of companies, and based upon weekly prices in Johannesburg and Cape Town. The index was compiled by the University of Stellenbosch, and later by the Reserve Bank of South Africa. The same sources were used for the gold index, which begins in 1925; however, the Banker’s Magazine index of South African Mining Shares traded on the London Stock Exchange has been used to extend the data back to 1910. The JSE All-Share Index is used beginning in January 1960. The Overall All-Share Index is a capitalization-weighted price index, using the Paasche formula, which is adjusted for capitalization and component changes. It includes all shares traded on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange. Sources include Banker’s Magazine (1888-1924 for Gold Shares), C.G.W. Schumann and A. E. Scheurkogel, Industrial and Commercial Share Price Indices in South Africa, Stellenbosch: Bureau for Economic Research, 1947 (1910-47), Reserve Bank of South Africa, Quarterly Bulletin, Johannesburg (1948-1959), Financial Mail (1960-).
The JSE Indices were revised in March 1999 when new sector indices were introduced, and they were further revised in February 2002 when the JSE joined with FTSE to calculate the FTSE/JSE Africa Indices. Where possible, the JSE calculated the indices back to June 30, 1995. When a new index is tied to an old index, the base is the value of the old index on December 31, 2001. All other indices have a base of 1000, while NSX indices have a base of 100.
The JSE All-Share Index is used beginning in January 1960. The Overall All-Share Index is a capitalization-weighted price index, using the Paasche formula, which is adjusted for capitalization and component changes. It includes all shares traded on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange. Sources include Banker's Magazine (1888-1924 for Gold Shares), C.G.W. Schumann and A. E. Scheurkogel, Industrial and Commercial Share Price Indices in South Africa, Stellenbosch: Bureau for Economic Research, 1947 (1910-47), Reserve Bank of South Africa, Quarterly Bulletin, Johannesburg (1948-1959), Financial Mail (1960-).

Name: Russia Moscow Index (MOEX) Composite
Periodicity:
Weekly From Sep 1993 To Mar 1994
Daily From Mar 1994 To Oct 2020
Metadata: The MICEX Index is calculated from September 22, 1997 (initial value is 100), using share prices in rubles. The MICEX Index has been constructed as a effective market capitalization-weighted value ratio for the most liquid shares of Russian issuers with daily chaining. It incorporates stocks specific free float factors, which are intended to ensure that the weight of a particular stock corresponds to the fraction of the registered capital that is actually available for public trading on the stock exchange. The MICEX Index is calculated on the basis of actual prices of shares included into the Index calculation base (the list of shares used for the Index calculation, which are formed by MICEX on expert judgment). The MICEX Index calculation base is reviewed by MICEX no more often than once a quarter.  Data for the AK&M Composite is used before 1997.

The index is based on prices generated in the electronic trading system Xetra®. Its calculation starts at 9.00 a.m. and ends with the prices from the Xetra closing auction at 5.30 p.m.
